snippet.textDisplay: A baby with a cough? Follow the advice of Corky, a waiter who never got sick. My wife worked with him decades ago and he said when you're dealing with customers who are often sick and you don't want to get sick take a half a teaspoon of Crystal powder vitamin C everyday or every other day and you'll never get sick. I gave it to a couple of parents who had four kids. All the kids got sick from school but the parents never did until one of them decided to do an experiment and stop taking the Vitamin C powder. They got sick in 2 days. They started taking it again and the next day they were fine. It works really well on infants too. You can get it on Amazon. It's vitamin C crystals by Bronson Laboratories and it costs about $30 for a kilogram in a white jug. It will last forever, but I keep three on my boat and give it to friends. You put it in water before you go to bed and it tastes like turbocharged lemonade. Never drink it in the morning because sometimes it will empty you and you don't want to be in a car stuck in traffic when that happens. If you take it at night it will make you sleep like a baby and you will wake up with that deep opioid dopamine feeling and say wow, I was really out deep. So it's a great sedative when you are sailing through nasty weather & need a short nap that's really deep. Anyway, I owe you a beer for getting Greta across the ocean as my other post at the other video described. You made my Friday night. Thank you. snippet.textDisplay: I love your description of dealing with the conditions and your "private" journal. Especially, "I looked at Nikki, judged HER reaction and went off shift.."  Made me laugh and think of a particularly rough trip on a Class 40 where half our crew were completely immobilized with sea sickness. I was on deck... we just had a little too much sail up for 45kts sustained... but the foredeck was so nasty we were "biding our time" before doing a headsail change... trying to decide if I absolutely HAD to go up there. I was "privately" almost convinced the rig was going to come down in the gusts above 40+ when we'd fly into the back of the wave in front of us.... but I kept looking at my watch mate, who was the rig designer, and thinking "he doesn't seem TOO worried".  It wasn't until years later when Chris (the rig designer) and I were discussing the trip when he admitted to me that HE had been staring at ME at the same time thinking "Well, Kate doesn't seem too worried"!  Ha! I guess we were lucky we did keep the rig :)!! Loving this video, great story!
snippet.textOriginal: I love your description of dealing with the conditions and your "private" journal. Especially, "I looked at Nikki, judged HER reaction and went off shift.."  Made me laugh and think of a particularly rough trip on a Class 40 where half our crew were completely immobilized with sea sickness. I was on deck... we just had a little too much sail up for 45kts sustained... but the foredeck was so nasty we were "biding our time" before doing a headsail change... trying to decide if I absolutely HAD to go up there. I was "privately" almost convinced the rig was going to come down in the gusts above 40+ when we'd fly into the back of the wave in front of us.... but I kept looking at my watch mate, who was the rig designer, and thinking "he doesn't seem TOO worried".  It wasn't until years later when Chris (the rig designer) and I were discussing the trip when he admitted to me that HE had been staring at ME at the same time thinking "Well, Kate doesn't seem too worried"!  Ha! I guess we were lucky we did keep the rig :)!! Loving this video, great story!

snippet.textDisplay:
"Report: U.S. the Global Leader for Reducing CO2 Emissions in 2019"
https://www.iea.org/articles/global-co2-emissions-in-2019 11 Feb 2020
The United States saw the largest decline in energy-related CO2 emissions in 2019 on a country basis – a fall of 140 Mt, or 2.9%, to 4.8 Gt. US emissions are now down almost 1 Gt from their peak in the year 2000, the largest absolute decline by any country over that period. A 15% reduction in the use of coal for power generation underpinned the decline in overall US emissions in 2019. Coal-fired power plants faced even stronger competition from natural gas-fired generation, with benchmark gas prices an average of 45% lower than 2018 levels. As a result, gas increased its share in electricity generation to a record high of 37%. Overall electricity demand declined because demand for air-conditioning and heating was lower as a result of milder summer and winter weather.
